\begin{frame}{Reasons for Home Bias}
	There are five main reasons put forward for \emph{home bias}
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
		\pause
	\item Exchange rate risk: Hau and Rey (2004)
	\item Transaction costs: Tesar and Werner (1996)
	\item Information asymmetries: Aherene et al (2004)
	\item Geographical proximity: Portes and Rey (2005)
	\item Behavioural bias: Huberman (2001)
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Exchange Rate Risk}
	Exchange rates are an additional risk for international investors
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
		\pause
	\item Exchange rate can be hedged
		\begin{itemize}
			\item active or passive investment (evidence suggest that active investment is not successful
		\end{itemize}
	\item Exchange rate can be treated as an additional \emph{asset class}
		\begin{itemize}
			\item \emph{currency overlay}
		\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\section{International Investment}

\begin{frame}{Globalisation}
The process of globalisation has called the benefits of international diversification into question
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\pause
\item Opening up of countries to trade has brought economic cycles more into synchronisation
\item Opening of capital markets has allowed capital to flow freely from one country to another. 
\item Structure is more \emph{risk-on/risk-off}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Country vs assets}
Given globalisation the question of whether international diversification should concentrate on countries or industries has emerged
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
		\pause
	\item Evidence suggests that industries have become more important but that countries still dominate
	\item Baca et al (2000) and Cavaliga et al. (2000) find that industries have become a more important part of diversification
	\item However, Brooke and De Negro (2002, 2004) find that much of the result is a consequence of the dot.com bubble and its deflation
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

